# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: guy-hecker
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:guy-hecker/1882-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1882 throughout the world.
[src:guy-hecker/1889-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1889 throughout the world.
[src:guy-hecker/1889-in-baseball] New York defeated Brooklyn, six games to three.
[src:guy-hecker/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The **1890 major league baseball season** began on April 17, 1890.
[src:guy-hecker/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The National League and newly founded Players' League regular seasons ended on October 4, with the Boston Beaneaters and Boston Reds as the NL and PL pennant winners, respectively.
[src:guy-hecker/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association regular season ended on October 15 and saw the Louisville Colonels the winners of the AA pennant.
[src:guy-hecker/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason between the AA and NL began with Game 1 of the seventh World's Championship Series on October 17 and ended with Game 7 on October 28.
[src:guy-hecker/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The series ended in a tie, with the Bridegrooms and Colonels each with three wins, and a tie game.
[src:guy-hecker/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The series was unique in that the Bridegrooms reached the series back-to-back, but with each season in a different league, a feat that has not been matched since.
[src:guy-hecker/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The Reds had floated a three-way Championship series with them and the AA & NL pennant winners, though the idea fell on deaf ears.
[src:guy-hecker/1890-major-league-baseball-season] This was the final season of a dual-league championship until the founding of the modern World Series in 1903 between the National League and American League.
[src:guy-hecker/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The major league world was in turmoil in 1890, as many of the best players had jumped to the "outlaw" Players' League.
[src:guy-hecker/1890-major-league-baseball-season] Although the Brotherhood only lasted the one season, it had a detrimental financial effect on the other two leagues, especially the Association, who would not survive the following season, merging into the National League in December 1891.
[src:guy-hecker/1890-major-league-baseball-season] Over the prior offseason, the Indianapolis Hoosiers and Washington Nationals of the National League, and Kansas City Cowboys of the American Association folded.
[src:guy-hecker/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The major-league status of the Federal League was confirmed by the Special Baseball Records Committee (as convened by then-Commissioner of Baseball William Eckert) in 1969.
[src:guy-hecker/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The 1890 schedule consisted of 140 games for all teams in the American Association, National League, and Players' League, each of which had eight active teams (the Baltimore Orioles would finish the Brooklyn Gladiators' schedule once they folded following their last game on August 25).
[src:guy-hecker/1890-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 20 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:guy-hecker/1890-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place by the American Association since the 1886 season and by the National League since the 1888 season.
[src:guy-hecker/1890-major-league-baseball-season] American Association Opening Day took place on April 17 featuring six teams, while National League and Players' League Opening Days took place on April 19, each featuring their eight teams.
[src:guy-hecker/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association would see its final day of the regular season on October 15 with a doubleheader between the Baltimore Orioles and Rochester Broncos.
[src:guy-hecker/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The National League would see its final day of the season on October 4, with a doubleheader between the Philadelphia Phillies and Cleveland Spiders.
[src:guy-hecker/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The Players' League would see its season end on the same day, with all eight teams playing.
[src:guy-hecker/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The 1890 World's Championship Series took place between October 17 and October 28.
[src:guy-hecker/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The 1890 season featured an extremely rare tripleheader—the first of three in National League and major-league history, when the Brooklyn Bridegrooms hosted the Pittsburgh Alleghenys on September 1 for three games.
[src:guy-hecker/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Gladiators, Cleveland Spiders, and Pittsburgh Alleghenys played in 17 neutral site games in which they were treated as the home team.
[src:guy-hecker/1890-major-league-baseball-season] 31 tie games (15 in AA, 9 in NL, 7 in PL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:guy-hecker/1890-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:guy-hecker/1890-major-league-baseball-season] Only records for National League teams are available.
[src:guy-hecker/1890-major-league-baseball-season] With the Brooklyn Bridegrooms transferring to the National League, which bans Sunday games, their three-season tenure playing Sunday games at Ridgewood Park in Ridgewood, New York ends.
[src:guy-hecker/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The 1890 season saw six teams playing at their respective ballparks for the last time, five of which moved into new ballparks for the start of the 1891 season while one team, the Brooklyn Gladiators, folded mid-season.
[src:guy-hecker/1890-pittsburgh-alleghenys-season] The **1890 Pittsburgh Alleghenys season** was the ninth season for the Pittsburgh Pirates franchise.
[src:guy-hecker/1890-pittsburgh-alleghenys-season] The team finished eighth and last in the National League with a record of 23–113–2 (.169), 66.5 games behind the Brooklyn Bridegrooms.
[src:guy-hecker/1890-pittsburgh-alleghenys-season] As of 2025, this remains the worst single-season record in the history of the Pittsburgh Pirates franchise.
[src:guy-hecker/1890-pittsburgh-alleghenys-season] The 1890 team also recorded the most losses and the second-fewest wins in a season (behind only the shortened 60-game 2020 season).
[src:guy-hecker/1890-pittsburgh-alleghenys-season] Their -16.5 pitching wins above replacement and 56 adjusted ERA+ represent the lowest marks for any team in a single season in MLB history.
[src:guy-hecker/1890-pittsburgh-alleghenys-season] This was the final season for the team with the name "Alleghenys," as the team changed its name to the Pittsburgh Pirates the next season, a name it has retained to the present day.
[src:guy-hecker/1890-pittsburgh-alleghenys-season] The Alleghenys' season essentially ended when most of its stars defected to the Pittsburgh Burghers of the Players' League.
[src:guy-hecker/1890-pittsburgh-alleghenys-season] With a decimated roster, the Alleghenys made a poor showing.
[src:guy-hecker/1890-pittsburgh-alleghenys-season] The 113 losses by the Alleghenys set a new major league record, breaking the old record of 111 set the previous year by the Louisville Colonels.
[src:guy-hecker/1890-pittsburgh-alleghenys-season] That record would stand until 1899, when the Cleveland Spiders lost 134 games, the all-time record.
[src:guy-hecker/1890-pittsburgh-alleghenys-season] Poor crowd attendance meant that this team played 97 of its 136 games on the road, finishing with a road record of 9-88.
[src:guy-hecker/1890-pittsburgh-alleghenys-season] The team's .093 road winning percentage is the lowest in MLB history for a minimum of 60 games, for comparison the 1899 Spiders road winning percentage was .098.
[src:guy-hecker/1890-pittsburgh-alleghenys-season] This would be the last time the Pittsburgh franchise reached the century mark in the loss column until 1917, when the team was known as the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:guy-hecker/2020-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The **2020 Pittsburgh Pirates season** was the franchise's 139th season overall, 134th season as a member of the National League, and 20th season at PNC Park.
[src:guy-hecker/2020-pittsburgh-pirates-season] On March 12, 2020, MLB announced that because of the ongoing COVID-19 pandemic, the start of the regular season would be delayed by at least two weeks in addition to the remainder of spring training being cancelled.
[src:guy-hecker/2020-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Four days later, it was announced that the start of the season would be pushed back indefinitely due to the recommendation made by the CDC to restrict events of more than 50 people for eight weeks.
[src:guy-hecker/2020-pittsburgh-pirates-season] On June 23, commissioner Rob Manfred unilaterally implemented a 60-game season.
[src:guy-hecker/2020-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Players reported to training camps on July 1 to resume spring training and prepare for a July 24 Opening Day.
[src:guy-hecker/2020-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The Pirates finished the season with an MLB worst record of 19–41.
[src:guy-hecker/2020-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The team's .317 winning percentage was their worst since 1952.
[src:guy-hecker/2020-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The Pirates technically set an MLB record for the fewest games won in any official season, finishing with one less win than the notorious 1899 Cleveland Spiders, although the 1899 Spiders played 154 games.
[src:guy-hecker/2020-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Because of the shortened season, and a winning percentage of .317 winning percentage being roughly equivalent to a 51–111 record in a 162-game season, the 19 wins is not generally recognized as one of baseball's worst records.
[src:guy-hecker/al-buckenberger] Buckenberger was born in Detroit, Michigan, and began his career as an infielder, and then manager for minor league teams in the Midwest.
[src:guy-hecker/al-buckenberger] In 1889 he became manager of the *Columbus Solons* of the American Association for two seasons.
[src:guy-hecker/al-buckenberger] After a year at the minor league Sioux City, Iowa based Sioux City Cornhuskers he joined the National League *Pittsburgh Pirates* from 1892 to 1894, and then the *St.
[src:guy-hecker/al-buckenberger] He managed the *Toronto Maple Leafs*, and the *Syracuse Stars* of the Eastern League for a year each, taking Syracuse to a first place finish in 1897.
[src:guy-hecker/al-buckenberger] He then managed the Eastern League *Rochester Bronchos* from 1899 to 1901, finishing first-second-first.
[src:guy-hecker/al-buckenberger] Following this he rejoined the National League as manager of the *Boston Beaneaters* from 1902 to 1904.
[src:guy-hecker/al-buckenberger] He returned to Rochester between 1905 and 1908.
[src:guy-hecker/al-buckenberger] Al Buckenberger also served as club president at Pittsburgh.
[src:guy-hecker/al-buckenberger] His biggest successes were finishing second in the American Association in 1890 and finishing second in the National League at Pittsburgh in 1893.
[src:guy-hecker/al-buckenberger] After his major league days he was part of a group, together with Francis Richter, editor of Sporting Life, and fellow manager Billy Barnie that tried and failed to resurrect the American Association.
[src:guy-hecker/al-buckenberger] Buckenberger died at age 56 in Syracuse, New York.
[src:guy-hecker/al-pratt-baseball] A native of Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania, Pratt was a Civil War veteran and baseball player.
[src:guy-hecker/al-pratt-baseball] Pratt was 5'7", 140 lbs., and compiled a 12–26 record in 43 professional games as a hurler.
[src:guy-hecker/al-pratt-baseball] In successive years with Cleveland, 1871–1872, Pratt hit .262 and .277 in 45 games with a total of 52 hits.
[src:guy-hecker/al-pratt-baseball] Pratt managed the Portsmouth, Ohio baseball team in 1868.
[src:guy-hecker/al-pratt-baseball] Afterward he was a member of the Forest City Club of Cleveland in the Professional League of Baseball Players.
[src:guy-hecker/al-pratt-baseball] This was the first professional league in America.
[src:guy-hecker/al-pratt-baseball] In 1880 Pratt founded the first major league club in Pittsburgh, the Alleghenys (later renamed the Pittsburgh Pirates), which joined the American Association.
[src:guy-hecker/al-pratt-baseball] Pratt celebrated his 90th birthday two days before his death in Pittsburgh on November 21, 1937.
[src:guy-hecker/al-pratt-baseball] He was buried, according to his request, attired in his Grand Army of the Republic uniform.
[src:guy-hecker/guy-hecker] Hecker acted as player-manager during the 1890 Pittsburgh Alleghenys season; in his only season managing a team, Hecker had a managerial record of 23–113–2 (.169).
[src:guy-hecker/guy-hecker] Hecker was born in Youngsville, Pennsylvania, in 1856.
[src:guy-hecker/guy-hecker] His family moved to Oil City, Pennsylvania, when he was a child.
[src:guy-hecker/guy-hecker] In 1877, Hecker started his professional baseball career with the Springfield Champion City of the League Alliance.
[src:guy-hecker/guy-hecker] He was listed at 6'0" tall and 190 pounds, and he batted and threw right-handed.
[src:guy-hecker/guy-hecker] After that season, Hecker moved back to Oil City, got married, and played for local teams through 1881.
[src:guy-hecker/guy-hecker] In 1882, Hecker joined the Louisville team of the new AA as a first baseman and backup pitcher to Tony Mullane.
[src:guy-hecker/guy-hecker] During his career, Hecker was known for his sharp baseball mind and leadership skills.
[src:guy-hecker/guy-hecker] He was friends and roommates with his teammate Pete Browning, an eccentric slugger.
[src:guy-hecker/guy-hecker] On September 19, 1882, Hecker became the second AA pitcher to throw a no-hitter; his teammate Mullane had thrown one a week earlier.
[src:guy-hecker/guy-hecker] Hecker finished the season with a 6–6 win–loss record, a 1.30 earned run average (ERA), and 33 strikeouts.
[src:guy-hecker/guy-hecker] In 1883, Mullane left the team, and Hecker became Louisville's primary pitcher.
[src:guy-hecker/guy-hecker] That season, Hecker went 28–23 with a 3.34 ERA and 164 strikeouts.
[src:guy-hecker/guy-hecker] Hecker was a power pitcher early in his major league career, with his key pitch being a "hard overhand drop curve." He was also a good hitter who sometimes played as a first baseman or outfielder when not pitching.
[src:guy-hecker/guy-hecker] Hecker had the best season of his career in 1884, winning the pitching version of the triple crown.
[src:guy-hecker/guy-hecker] He went 52–20 and led the AA with 670.2 innings pitched, 72 complete games, 52 wins, a 1.80 ERA, 385 strikeouts, and a 171 ERA+.
[src:guy-hecker/guy-hecker] His 52 wins are tied for the fourth-most during a single season in major league history.
[src:guy-hecker/guy-hecker] In 1886, Hecker suffered from an arm injury.
[src:guy-hecker/guy-hecker] He became a finesse pitcher and spent more time at first base for the rest of his career afterward.
[src:guy-hecker/guy-hecker] He also developed a rivalry with Louisville's new top pitcher, Toad Ramsey, which threatened to split the team.
[src:guy-hecker/guy-hecker] Despite all that, Hecker went 26–23 that season with a 2.87 ERA and 133 strikeouts.
[src:guy-hecker/guy-hecker] He had his best season as a hitter, leading the AA with a .341 batting average and posting a 161 OPS+.
[src:guy-hecker/guy-hecker] During the second game of a doubleheader against Baltimore on August 15, 1886, Hecker went six-for-seven at the plate, hitting three home runs and scoring seven runs.
[src:guy-hecker/guy-hecker] He is the only major league player to ever score seven runs in a game, and he is the only pitcher with six hits in a nine-inning game.
[src:guy-hecker/guy-hecker] A new rule change in 1887 limited pitcher movement on the mound to one forward step.
[src:guy-hecker/guy-hecker] This forced Hecker to abandon his usual "running start" delivery and hurt his performance.
[src:guy-hecker/guy-hecker] He finished the season with a record of 18–12, a 4.16 ERA, and 58 strikeouts.
[src:guy-hecker/guy-hecker] In 1888, Hecker went 8–17 with a 3.39 ERA and 63 strikeouts.
[src:guy-hecker/guy-hecker] In 1889, Hecker went 5–13 with a 5.59 ERA and 33 strikeouts.
[src:guy-hecker/guy-hecker] Louisville released him on September 17 of that year.
[src:guy-hecker/guy-hecker] In 1890, Hecker joined the Pittsburgh Alleghenys of the National League as a player-manager.
[src:guy-hecker/guy-hecker] As a pitcher, Hecker went 2–9 with a 5.11 ERA and 32 strikeouts.
[src:guy-hecker/guy-hecker] Pittsburgh had a record of 23–113 and finished in last place.
[src:guy-hecker/guy-hecker] During Hecker's major league career, he appeared in 336 games as a pitcher, 322 as a first baseman, and 75 as an outfielder.
[src:guy-hecker/guy-hecker] As a hitter, he had a .282 batting average, 19 home runs, 278 runs batted in, and a 117 OPS+.
[src:guy-hecker/guy-hecker] In the 2001 book *The New Bill James Historical Baseball Abstract*, Bill James ranked Hecker as the seventh-best pitcher/hitter combination in baseball history.
[src:guy-hecker/guy-hecker] In 1891, Hecker was a player-manager for Fort Wayne of the Northwestern League.
[src:guy-hecker/guy-hecker] In 1892, Hecker was a player-manager for the Jacksonville Lunatics of the Illinois-Iowa League.
[src:guy-hecker/guy-hecker] During the next few years, Hecker settled in Oil City, managed local teams, and was involved in the oil business.
[src:guy-hecker/guy-hecker] Later in life, he and his wife ran a grocery store in Wooster, Ohio.
[src:guy-hecker/guy-hecker] Hecker died in Wooster in 1938, at age 82, and was buried at Wooster Cemetery.
